Hans: Can‘t it be acceptable in the sense of „acts like a bad person“ as opposed to „acting in an inferior way“?
Not sure, since ly-adverbs are difficult for German speakers and I may have absorbed this over the years.

@Hobby Gardener - there is an unfortunate “rule” that has been drilled into people by English teachers that adverbs must always end in -ly.

In English, words of manner of one syllable were used as adverbs without that unneeded -ly. Grammar types have near obliterated that, quick. They haven’t gone slow in removing another simple English form in favor of a needless rule-making.

Go north, walk slow, do good, remain near, pay dear, hold fast, … all actually correct English, being hounded out by teachers over the past century.

@Meg 

LOVE TAP is a very common expression which to me is most commonly used when you’re parallel parking, and the only space your car will fit into at all is so tight that you have to hit the other cars’ bumpers to get the job done. A very New York expression, in my mind. At least among the driving set. 

As to the repetition, the only rule is that a word can’t be repeated in a clue and its own answer. That’s all.

@Russ Johnston 

The NATO agreement covers only territories in Europe and North America, even fully integrated parts of NATO countries in other areas. So Réunion is not covered, nor is French Guiana, or even Hawaii. 

Maybe that’s what the clue was getting at, though it was a bit clumsy in its phrasing.

@Anita 

