@Mean Old Lady 

Now in a lot of schools they don't have that special ed classroom and the kids are placed in with general ed students. In some cases that works out fairly well, but in others it can be detrimental to both groups.

My wife's students were mostly high functioning or intellectually normal, just blind or potentially heading that way, so they were in regular ed, and she'd pull them from study hall or occasionally from classes for testing—they got extra time and could get eye strain/headaches, so got the questions read to them in her office.

@Xword Junkie Not sure why "this Old Man" doesn't fit the theme.  Not hat I ever called Dad my old man, but others do.  And it ties in with 49A, NICK.
Now the song is stuck in my head...This old man, he played one, he played nick knack on my thumb, with a nick knack paddy whack, give a dog a bone, this old man came....
Now I hope it's everyone's head!!

@Cloudy Rockwell I guess I'm not sure what the "theme" is supposed to be. For "Pop corn?" we have DADJOKE. OK, that makes some sense---Pop refers to DAD and corn to JOKE. Similarly with "Pop quizzes?" and PATERNITYTESTS---Pop connects to PATERNITY and quizzes to TESTS.

But then we get "Pop song?" and THISOLDMAN. Well, OLDMAN connects to POP but it's at the end of the entry, and THIS has nothing to with the word song. THISOLDMAN is simply the title of a song that includes a phrase meaning father (as pop does).

If there's a solid theme in all this, it's certainly not working for me. Glad others were untroubled.

